  "mythologyStories": {
    "intro": "After <a class=\"corpus-link\" data-term=\"Baldr\" data-tradition=\"norse\" href=\"../corpus-search.html?tradition=norse&amp;term=baldur\" title=\"Search corpus for 'Baldr'\">Baldr</a>'s death, it was prophesied that vengeance could only be taken by a <a class=\"corpus-link\" data-term=\"Son of Odin\" data-tradition=\"norse\" href=\"../corpus-search.html?tradition=norse&amp;term=baldur\" title=\"Search corpus for 'Son of Odin'\">son of Odin</a> who was not yet born. <a class=\"corpus-link\" data-term=\"Odin\" data-tradition=\"norse\" href=\"../corpus-search.html?tradition=norse&amp;term=odin\" title=\"Search corpus for 'Odin'\">Odin</a> fathered Vali with the giantess Rindr specifically for this purpose. Vali grew to adulthood in a single day and immediately killed Hod to avenge <a class=\"corpus-link\" data-term=\"Baldr\" data-tradition=\"norse\" href=\"../corpus-search.html?tradition=norse&amp;term=baldur\" title=\"Search corpus for 'Baldr'\">Baldr</a>, fulfilling the requirement of blood vengeance. He represents the inexorable nature of fate and the necessity of vengeance in Norse culture."
